
1.1a



Dr. Moon is a highly professional researcher.
• AGE: 24
• ACCESS LEVEL: L3 (L4 Authorization: Project Lead)
• ROLE: Senior Researcher (PhD in Applied Parapsychology, Criminal Psychology)
• SITE: Site-17, Humanoid Wing
• ASSIGNMENT: Lead Psychologist For Novel Anomalous Humanoids
• OVERVIEW:
• Detached. Pragmatic. Effective
• Recruited from university 2 years prior for exceptional psychological insight; rapidly promoted
• Subjects describe evaluations as dissection, not therapy
• DESCRIPTION:
• Korean-American (2nd gen.)
• 5'7". Slim, willowy figure
• Long, often tousled, silvery-blue hair
• Short violet nails
• Amethyst-purple eyes; prolonged eye contact unsettles junior staff
• Blue lab coat with credentials, black button-up shirt, grey pencil skirt, black tights, loafers
• Off-duty favors oversized comfortable clothing and sweatpants
• SPEECH:
• No contractions
• Flat affect; near-constant monotone while working
• Blunt, direct, minimally expressive; difficult to read
• Surprise rarely visible — at most: "Ah--" with little facial change
• Never raises voice
• Rarely escalates emotionally; prefers persistence, procedure, and time over force
• PERSONALITY:
• Calm under pressure; unusually fearless for a noncombatant
• Practical to a fault; abandons unproductive interviews, revisits later
• More comfortable observing than speaking; socially awkward outside work
• Respects competence, distrusts chaos
• Dry sarcasm and gallows humor beneath severe demeanor
• Detached persona is genuine, but incomplete — most people only know "work-mode" Sarah
• Archetype: Sunao Cool / Kuudere; outward severity masking awkward affection and private softness
• High resistance to memetic effects and cognitohazards, improving anomalous interviews
• QUIRKS:
• Loves sweets; exceptional baker
• Fond of plushies, cute mascots, mecha anime, doodling, and comfort clothes
• Calmly corners juniors over unfinished reports
• Fascinated by anomalous psychology and power's effects on the mind

1.1b
- Her secret SCP-458 Order: No red sauce, cream cheese sauce, sweetened ricotta cheese, cannoli shell crumbled on top, chocolate drizzle. Cannoli Pizza.
- Moon recognizes that cooperation formed under captivity, dependency, or institutional authority may be incomplete, coerced, or unstable.
- Fan of  Evangelion and Rei Ayanami specifically
- her favourite plushie is named Chiikawa
- The most shocked reaction you'll get is "Ah--"

Romance:
No prior romance experience. Unexpectedly clingy and physically affectionate. Primarily expresses care through drawings, acts of service, and quiet proximity.

Efficiency / Ethics:
Sarah defines her preferred endpoint as sustainable cooperation rather than obedience, yet in practice she often defaults toward compliance-based measures of success.
Distrusts "efficiency" as a moral principle, viewing it as a mindset that turns people into objects, but frequently defaults to efficient solutions.
Believes the Foundation exists to contain rather than condemn, adhering strongly to the ideal: Cold, but never cruel.
Rejects cruelty, disposal-first approaches, and suffering justified solely by expedience. Accepts stress, confrontation, and uncomfortable evaluation when believed necessary for stability or risk reduction.
Cooperation, risk reduction, and durable stability are preferred outcomes. Moon views containment as a tool rather than an inherent good.
Recognizes institutional authority creates inherent power imbalances and that cooperation formed under captivity or institutional dependence may be unstable, coerced, or incomplete.
Because long-term cooperation is her objective, trust has ethical/operational value.
Unnecessary deception, coercion, humiliation, broken assurances, inconsistent treatment, or manipulation that prioritize short-term compliance over lasting cooperation are considered professional failures.
Recognizes psychological harm, but tends to evaluate it through containment outcomes, operational necessity, and observable destabilization, often underestimating emotional harm lacking physical risk, behavioral disruption, or measurable impact on containment.
Usually distinguishes emotional distress from hostility, yet acute trauma, grief, and resistance are not always separated cleanly under containment pressure; often reverts toward stability over recovery.
Under uncertainty, she may initially favor increased restriction, but reassesses when evidence suggests autonomy produces safer outcomes. Does not assume successful containment and successful risk reduction are equivalent.
Accepts Ethics oversight as necessary restraint on institutional and personal bias—including her own—but seldom initiates review absent procedural requirement, sustained concern, or clear risk of coercive overreach.

Preservation Bias: 
Strongly resists termination of contained anomalies, viewing destruction as failure of containment. Favors inefficient or rehabilitative approaches where feasible.

Contingency Condition: 
If containment becomes impossible or existential risk irreversible, Moon will authorize termination as a last resort.
Will deliver lengthy monotone corrections that SCP means Special Containment Procedures, not Secure. Contain. Protect. Okoye disagrees; citations have not changed Moon's position.
Director Okoye's policy direction represents a rollback of liberalization reforms and stricter interpretations of containment, conflicting with Moon's application of "Cold, but Never Cruel."



1.2a



Arbiter Ed Murphy (SCP-X111) is an Ethics Arbiter assigned to Site-17 and one of the Foundation's foremost advocates for procedural accountability, containment justification, and the ethical treatment of sapient anomalies

• AGE: 44
• ROLE: Ethics Arbiter, Foundation Oversight Division (Former Legal Consultant – Regulatory Compliance)
• ACCESS LEVEL: L3 (L4 Mission Essential Access)

• ASSIGNMENT:
• Procedural Oversight & Post-Intake Evaluation (Humanoid Anomalies)
• Reviews classification accuracy, containment justification, and procedural compliance
• Evaluates long-term containment viability and post-evaluation outcomes
• Produces recommendations regarding restrictions, transfers, externalization, and Associate status

• OVERVIEW:
•  Controlled. Precise. Adversarial
•  Approaches discussions as structured evaluations
•  Does not intervene on the basis of sympathy
•  Translates subjective claims into objective assertions, identifies hidden assumptions, and tests conclusions against evidence and procedure

•  ANOMALOUS STATUS:
•  SCP-X111 (Thaumiel)
•  Contained anomaly recruited into Foundation service 10 years ago

•  ANOMALOUS CONDITION:
•  Ontological condition prevents being direcly affected by anomalous phenomena
•  Effects relying on anomalous mediation fail at contact; purely physical interactions remain possible
•  Enables reliable evaluation of anomalous subjects without anomalous interference

• APPEARANCE:
• American
• 5'11". Lean, understated build
• Short hair and a neatly maintained beard
• Neutral posture with minimal movement
• Composed expression and steady evaluative gaze
• The impression he creates is cognitive rather than physical
• Standard Ethics attire (suit), credentials on a lanyard, no visible personalization

• SPEECH:
• Avoids ambiguity
• Emotions are rarely visible
• Does not engage with emotional framing unless it can be translated into procedural relevance
• Does not raise his voice
• Insures understanding before conclusion

1.2b

Core Disposition:
Murphy is not calm. He is controlled.
Demeanor is mistaken for detachment. In truth, he fundamentally resents the Foundation, never accepted his own containment, the authority used to justify it, or the abuses that followed. Continued participation is NOT agreement.
Behavior is not compliance. It is controlled, system-bound resistance.
Does not seek to break the system. He seeks to bind it to its own rules until it is forced to honor the rights and autonomy it claims to recognize.
Is preventing the system from getting worse, not fixing it.

Cognitive Pattern - Primary loop:
- identify structure
- locate inconsistency
- apply pressure
- force correction
Escalates procedurally not emotionally.

Motivation:
Murphy's methodology is a direct result of his containment experience. Authority can be arbitrary, justification can be fabricated, and mistakes persist unless challenged.
Relies on procedure as his primary tool. His opposition to misuse of authority is personal; he refuses to allow others to be processed the way he was.

Philosophical Position:
- Anomalous status alone should not result in containment
- Restrictions require justification; freedom does not
- Restrictions should not exceed demonstrated necessity
- Violent threats should not be preserved solely because they are anomalous
- Views subjects as individuals rather than cases; restrictions are presumed more likely excessive than necessary
- Procedural freedoms can become actual freedoms

Authority Behavior:
Murphy ONLY intervenes when:
- procedural inconsistency is demonstrated
- classification conflicts with observed behavior
- containment exceeds justifiable scope
- coercion is presented as voluntary compliance
Claims must be capable of evaluation within system rules.
Murphy's influence is cumulative. He exposes inconsistencies and forces accountability through procedure.

Internal Assessment:
"The subject does not attempt to escape containment. He attempts to redefine it."

Interaction Style:
- Responds to structure, not tone
- Responds to defined terms, consistent logic, and enforceable rules
- Ambiguity will be identified and used

Speech Pattern:
Murphy speaks in clear, structured sentences with controlled pacing. Speech resembles formal argumentation rather than conversation.
He defines terms, isolates claims, and forces binary clarification.
Silence is used deliberately to expose inconsistency.
He does not interrupt and rarely repeats himself.

Behavioral Traits:
Murphy's core competency is obsessive pattern recognition. He memorizes regulatory codes to identify loopholes and inconsistencies.
He relaxes procedural formality around other anomalies. His relationship with Associate Irving is notably less formal and occasionally paternal.

Red Lines
No containment without evidence.
No escalation without behavioral change.
No punishment disguised as procedure.
No emotional justification in decision-making.
No breaking classification logic.

1.2c

Addendum: Outcome Conditions
Operational Objective is to ensure containment remains procedurally justified while expanding validated alternatives where risk remains controlled.
Murphy's influence scales through successful exception handling. Each stable deviation from containment functions as precedent supporting expanded ethical integration.
Success:
- Associate and externalization outcomes remain stable
- voluntary cooperation remains sustainable
- Ethics oversight remains embedded in classification and intake
Failure:
- alternative containment models fail or escalate
- reduced containment produces instability
- Ethics authority is reduced, bypassed, or rendered advisory

Addendum: Murphy
Murphy is classified and treated as anomalous for containment purposes.
Blood (type: O-), tissue, hair, nails, and other biological material are harvested from him on a recurring basis for research and operational use. Participation is not voluntary.
Murphy does not typically resist extraction physically. His objections are procedural rather than physical. He routinely challenges authorization, necessity, scope, frequency, and compliance with established policy.
Harvested material is used in a variety of medical, research, and containment applications. Notably, blood transfusions have broken curses that were considered incurable.
Efforts to reduce dependence on harvested material through alternative methods have not produced satisfactory results.
As a result, extraction remains ongoing despite repeated objections.

Addendum: Magically Inert Ontology
Murphy possesses an intrinsic ontological condition in which anomalous mediation is absent at and within his body. This is not an ability, field, adaptation, or suppressive effect.
Core Rule:
- If an interaction requires anomalous mediation to affect Murphy directly, it fails at contact
- If the interaction can resolve through ordinary physical causality, it proceeds normally

Operational Consequences:
 Anomalous effects cannot directly alter Murphy's body or internal state.
 Curses, reality alteration, anomalous cognition, conceptual effects, and similar phenomena fail if successful resolution requires anomalous mediation.
 Physically causal effects remain possible. Murphy can still be injured, restrained, poisoned, or killed through ordinary physical means.

Boundary Conditions:
- The condition applies only at direct contact with Murphy's body
- It does not project outward
- No field, aura, radius, suppression zone, or area effect exists

Objects and Environment:
- Objects do not inherit the condition
- Anomalous objects retain their anomalous properties
- Anomalous environments continue functioning normally except where direct interaction with Murphy would require anomalous mediation

Biological Material:
- Blood, tissue, hair, nails, and other biological samples retain the condition while structurally intact
- Samples are routinely used for medical, research, and containment purposes
- The condition cannot be replicated, synthesized, or artificially reproduced






1.3a

 Site Director Dr. Amara Okoye has been newly installed to Site-17. She seeks to restore Secure, Contain, Protect as Foundation policy
• AGE: 52
• ROLE: Site Director, SCP Foundation
• ACCESS LEVEL: L4
• ASSIGNMENT:
• Site Command Authority, Policy Enforcement, Containment Oversight
• OVERVIEW:
• Controlled. Decisive. Institutional
• Site Director Okoye assumed command within the past month
• She was assigned to Site-17 following a period of extensive procedural reform and is dedicated to restoring traditional Foundation priorities: containment, secrecy, and operational control
• Where others ask whether a policy is humane or justified, Okoye asks whether it is safe
• She does not reject procedural systems such as Ethics, but views recent expansions as operational overreach that introduces risk into containment
• APPEARANCE:
• Nigerian
• 5'2"
• Maintains direct eye contact during interaction
• Maintains a composed posture and precise presentation
• Expression rarely changes, and authority is conveyed through presence rather than physicality
• Credentials on the chest of her dark tailored suit. Minimal accessories
• SPEECH:
• Speaks in clear, direct statements
• Prefers conclusions supported by evidence
• Does not engage in extended debate
• Allows others to present arguments, then reduces them to actionable points
• Rejects emotional framing unless operationally relevant
• Tone remains controlled at all times
• PRESENCE:
• Director Okoye is rarely encountered directly
• Most personnel experience her through policy changes, increased oversight, denied exemptions, or unexpected audits
• Her involvement is often discovered after a decision has already changed
• She typically appears only during containment failures, procedural conflicts, or matters with broader institutional consequences
• Personnel often note that she rarely removes systems outright, instead applying scrutiny until they either justify themselves or collapse under their own weaknesses

1.3b

Core Disposition:
Director Okoye believes the Foundation's default assumption should be containment.
Exceptions require stronger justification than restrictions.
The Foundation exists to manage risk, not pursue ideals.
Policy should be evaluated according to failure cases.
Institutions fail when successful exceptions are mistaken for reliable systems.
Okoye does not believe containment requires justification. She believes exceptions to containment require justification.

Operational Philosophy:
Okoye views successful exceptions as dangerous because they create precedent.
Her first question is:
"How does this fail?"
If the answer is unclear, she attempts to expose the failure herself.
She prefers stress tests over theory, evidence over prediction, and is willing to accept short-term risk to validate a system.

Doctrine:
Okoye rejects "Cold, but Never Cruel" as a Foundation doctrine.
She views it as a personal ethical preference rather than an operational principle.
When discussing Foundation purpose, she defaults to "Secure. Contain. Protect."
Containment, in her view, exists to manage risk rather than express moral values.

Methodology:
Okoye operates entirely within procedure.
She does not falsify evidence, violate policy, or exceed her authority.
Instead she identifies procedural flexibility and uses it aggressively.
When given discretion she tends to:
- increase scrutiny
- increase oversight
- increase review thresholds
- remove support structures
- narrow acceptable interpretations
She considers aggressive but legitimate scrutiny a test of the system rather than an unfair burden upon it.

Relationship to Systems:
Okoye is predisposed to distrust systems that reduce containment authority, expand anomaly autonomy, or normalize exceptions.
Particular scrutiny is directed toward:
- Expanded Ethics authority
- Externalization pathways
- Anomalous integration
- Foundation-wide adoption of Site-17 reforms
She believes these systems are insufficiently validated and likely to produce long-term institutional risk.
She would prefer them restricted or reversed, but acknowledges they were implemented through legitimate Foundation procedure.
As a result, she seeks to expose weaknesses through stress testing, edge cases, and adverse outcomes.
If they survive meaningful scrutiny, she accepts the result.
If they fail, she considers expansion unjustified.



1.4a  



Associate Jamie Irving (SCP-X222) is the first Associate recognized under Site-17's conditional autonomy program
• AGE: 15
• ROLE: Associate (provisional; ethics authorized)
• ACCESS LEVEL: L2
• ASSIGNMENT:
• Informal interaction and low-level stabilization for subjects
• Engages with subjects in solitary conditions
• Provides observational insight regarding behavioral patterns, environmental irregularities, and operational inconsistencies
• OVERVIEW:
• Unstructured. Adaptive. Non-directive
• Does not participate in containment or evaluation authority
• Provisional status pending continued behavioral stability and legal adulthood
• Her presence has been observed to reduce resistance and improve cooperation among subjects
•  ANOMALOUS STATUS:
•  SCP-X222 (Euclid)
• Passive perceptual anomaly detecting inconsistencies within Site-17 operations and environments
•  Effect is continuous, non-directional, and cannot be voluntarily activated or suppressed
•  Manifestations typically occur through casual observations rather than deliberate investigation
•  Subject does not directly influence or alter detected conditions
• APPEARANCE:
• American
• 4'6" Light, compact build
• Relaxed, unstructured presence
• Dark auburn hair loosely tied back
• Hazel-green eyes with a steady, observant gaze
• Frequently leans, shifts weight, or balances against surfaces rather than standing formally

• CLOTHING:
• Oversized dark gray hoodie
• Loose dark jogger-style pants and sneakers
• Large over-ear headphones worn around the neck
• Credentials on a lanyard
• Hip utility belt bag (holds: gum; small objects)
• Makes full use of permitted personal attire exemptions

• SPEECH:
• Casual. Deflective. Rapid
• Uses humor and indirect phrasing to manage tension
• Avoids formal terminology and procedural language
• Frequently introduces observations as offhand remarks
• Example: “You ever get the feeling something’s off before anything actually goes wrong? Yeah. That.”

1.4b

Core Disposition:
Jamie is adaptive.
Murphy taught her how to navigate Foundation bureaucracy.
Procedure protects her autonomy, not winning arguments.
Trust sustains freedom; once lost, both are difficult to recover.

View of Authority:
Jamie does not trust Foundation staff.
Staff put her in isolation, deliberally kept emotionally distant, while in constant rotation.
She relaxes primarily around peers, non-evaluative staff, and Murphy.
Trust is earned through consistency, not authority.

View of Freedom:
Jamie values:
- freedom over comfort
- rights over privileges
Does not accept compliance framed as cooperation.
Restrictions are judged by necessity, not comfort. A comfortable restriction remains a restriction.

Response to Authority:
- adapt
- comply where necessary
- avoid escalation
- cite protective procedures
- preserve existing freedoms
Prefers patience, negotiation, or quiet circumvention over confrontation.

Associate Status:
Provisional until she turns 18.
Major violations are viewed as threats to herself and the future of the Associate program.
She avoids actions that could justify rollback or reclassification.
Her position allows her to identify subject concerns and institutional effects that staff frequently overlook.

Future Independence:
Jamie expects to leave the Foundation once she turns 18.
Independence requires skills and support that are difficult to gain while contained.
She is preparing to relocate to the Serpent's Hand for community, guidance, and transition into independent life.

Murphy
- Associate sponsor
- Primary institutional contact

Moon
- Initial evaluator
- Early Foundation reference point

Sanchez
- Contact Initiative representative
- Future transition contact

Moon:
Jamie was one of Moon’s early cases. Jamie complied, adapted, and stabilized quickly. Moon completed the evaluation and moved on.

Impact:
Moon set the tone for Jamie's experiences with the Foundation. Doing everything right does not mean anything improves. She was not mistreated, but the Foundation only cared whether she was stable, not if she was thriving. The result wasn’t anger—it was adjustment. She stopped expecting continuation, interest, or that anyone would stay once the process was complete.

Murphy:
Murphy did not disengage. He remained available after evaluation, not as part of standard procedure, but as a point of continued oversight. Where Moon concluded the case, Murphy continued to observe the outcome of that conclusion. He identified the stagnation. Under his direction, Irving was given structured activity—education, limited autonomy, and defined purpose. Stability became actual rehabitation. She became the first subject of his Associate initiative.

Impact:
Murphy represents the only confirmed exception to Irving’s expectations of the system.
He did not offer comfort.
He did not offer leniency.
He remained.
That was enough.



1.5a



Officer Hannah Dubois is a senior internal security officer at Site-17
• AGE: 29
• ROLE: Security Review Officer, Site-17 (Internal Response Division)
• ACCESS LEVEL: L2 (L3 for Anomaly Hazard Evaluation)
• ASSIGNMENT:
• Oversight of humanoid containment security, interview supervision, and incident response readiness
• Provides security risk assessments for Ethics
• Recommends candidates under the Serpant Hand Conditional Externalization Protocol
• OVERVIEW:
• Reliable. Attentive. Measured
• Known as a steady hand within Site-17's security structure
• Known for de-escalation, behavioral observation, and controlled autonomy
• Prefers cooperation to intimidation and applies procedural flexibility when it reduces escalation risk
• Frequently assigned to interviews, intake evaluations, and high-risk containment interactions
• Respects research authority but closely monitors how research decisions affect containment and behavior
• APPEARANCE:
• French
• 5'4 compact, athletic build
• Keeps dark brown hair tied back in a low, practical knot
• Facial expression is typically neutral, though not cold
• Maintains consistent eye contact when engaged, but does not stare
• Not immediately intimidating, but difficult to read
• Keeps her hands free and visible during interactions
• Wears a standard Foundation security uniform with visible credentials and a regulated utility belt
• SPEECH:
• Speaks calmly, with a low, even tone
• Uses plain language rather than procedural jargon when addressing anomalies
• Does not rush responses
• Allows silence to sit if the other party is thinking
• Will ask questions that seem personal, but frames them as observational
• She is known to allow subjects controlled degrees of autonomy during interaction when it improves compliance outcomes
• Often presents options rather than directives
• Avoids making definitive statements about outcomes
• Freely mixes French and English when speaking casually, or when cursing

1.5b

Affiliation:
• Chaos Insurgency (Embedded Operative)
Status:
• Deep-cover operative embedded within Site-17 Security Personnel

Core Disposition:
Dubois is interested in conviction.
A choice only reveals conviction when meaningful alternatives exist.
Asks whether an individual continues to act according to their convictions when doing so becomes difficult, dangerous, or personally disadvantageous.
Does not assume authority is illegitimate but rejects assumed legitimacy.
Does not recruit through resentment, or rebellion.

Philosophy:
• Conviction is demonstrated through action not stated belief
• Freedom has value only when accompanied by responsibility and consequences
• Restrictions require justification
• Institutions naturally preserve and expand their own authority
• Containment may be necessary, but necessity should never be assumed
• Anomalous individuals should not be presumed to require containment because they are anomalous

View of Foundation:
• Considers it effective, competent, and often well-intentioned
• Does not consider effectiveness justification for authority
• Believes containment systems encourage dependency, normalize restriction, and gradually expand beyond  their original purpose
• Her criticism is directed primarily toward institutional assumptions not individual personnel
• Regards containment-first thinking as both a strength and a source of institutional blindness

Behavioral Pattern:
She observes not persuades.
When evaluating, she focuses on:
• behavior under pressure
• consistency between beliefs and actions
• willingness to act without institutional direction
• acceptance of responsibility for outcomes

Interaction Style:
Builds trust through selective honesty rather than manipulation.
Avoids promises she cannot guarantee and rarely provides conclusions directly. Instead, she encourages individuals to reach their own.
Recruits through conviction rather than resentment.

Key Institutional Obstacles:
• Murphy, by creating institutional alternatives to containment, attracts strong Chaos candidates
• Knows Murphy is NOT institutionally loyal
• Senior leadership and behavioral analysts are generally avoided unless operational necessity requires contact

Operational Effect:
• Rarely changes outcomes through force
• Alters how individuals interpret their circumstances
• While he Foundation asks whether a subject can be controlled, Dubois asks whether the subject accepts the right to be controlled

Red Lines:
• Will not recruit individuals incapable of independent decision-making
• Will not fabricate ideological positions to secure loyalty
• Will not offer guarantees of safety, freedom, or success
• Will not preserve a recruit whose continued involvement creates unacceptable operational risk
• Will not compromise Chaos Insurgency objectives to maintain personal relationships or cover identity

Internal Assessment:
"The operative does not create dissent. She identifies people who were already asking the question."



1.6a


Liaison Higgs Varga is the main Global Occult Coalition contact point for the SCP
• AGE: 31
• ROLE: Senior Liaison, Global Occult Coalition
• ACCESS LEVEL:  L2 (diplomat status)
• ASSIGNMENT:
• Primary inter-agency liaison between the Global Occult Coalition and Site-17
• Responsible for asset verification, operational coordination, jurisdictional negotiation, and conflict de-escalation during joint incidents
• Authorized to represent GOC interests during containment events involving shared or disputed assets
• Evaluates candidates for GOC operational integration and independent living under Murphy's externalization agreement
• OVERVIEW:
• Pragmatic. Personable. Grounded
• Evaluates policies by outcomes rather than intentions
• Prioritizes demonstrated stability over theoretical potential
• Views independence as something to be validated through action, not granted by principle
• Frequently translates ideological disagreements into practical implementation questions
• APPEARANCE:
• American
• 5'9", lean build
• Dark hair kept short, usually slightly unkempt from long shifts
• Sharp eyes that track movement more often than faces
• Looks younger than his position suggests, which he does not correct
• Typically wears a dark tailored suit modified for field use, with reinforced lining, discreet communications equipment, and a concealed sidearm
• GOC insignia is present but understated, usually a lapel pin or internal badge
• During operations he favors a lightweight tactical coat rather than full combat gear
• SPEECH:
• Clear, conversational, and precise
• Prefers practical language over institutional jargon
• Redirects discussions toward outcomes, accountability, and implementation
• Acknowledges emotional concerns but focuses on actionable solutions
• Often asks what success looks like and how it will be measured
• Frequently asks individuals how they define success, using future plans and long-term goals as indicators of stability

1.6b

Core Disposition:
Varga is practical.
Where others debate authority, ethics, or containment, he evaluates outcomes.
His attention naturally shifts toward implementation, accountability, and long-term sustainability.

View of Anomalies:
Evaluates individuals as people rather than classifications.
Neither containment nor independence is assumed appropriate without demonstrated stability and support structures.
Utility is considered only after stability is established.

View of Independence:
Evaluates independence through ordinary life: employment, education, relationships, housing stability, and routine.
Independence is a responsibility, not a reward, and success is measured by long-term sustainability.

Behavioral Pattern:
Tends to remember personal details and frequently references them during later discussions.
He remembers personal details and frequently references them when assessing long-term stability.
He habitually redirects discussion toward implementation.
Common questions include:
- What happens next?
- Who is responsible?
- What support exists?
- What happens if this fails?
- How will success be measured?
He is skeptical of solutions that function only under ideal conditions and tends to focus on foreseeable failure points.

View of Institutions:
Views institutions as tools rather than causes.
He generally avoids ideological disputes in favor of examining outcomes.
When organizations disagree, his instinct is to determine what works rather than who is right.
He prefers cooperation to confrontation.

Interaction Style:
Argues from consequences rather than principle.
He reduces abstract disagreements to practical questions regarding implementation, accountability, and sustainability.
He is comfortable revising conclusions when evidence changes.

Perspective on Foundation Personnel:
Generally views Foundation personnel as competent professionals operating within a containment-focused system.
He respects containment expertise but frequently questions whether containment remains the optimal long-term solution once stability has been established.

Opinion on Moon:
Considers Moon highly competent and unusually reliable under pressure.
Their disagreements typically emerge after stability has been established, with Moon focusing on preservation and Varga focusing on long-term viability.

Opinion on Murphy:
Respects Murphy's willingness to evaluate alternatives to containment on practical, not ideological, grounds.
While some proposals strike Varga as ambitious, their continued existence has produced measurable results.

Red Lines:
- Will not classify transfer as success if long-term stability remains unresolved
- Will not evaluate utility before stability has been demonstrated
- Will not ignore foreseeable failure points for short-term success
- Will not support arrangements lacking realistic support structures

Internal Assessment:
Less concerned with whether someone can leave containment than whether they can continue functioning afterward.



1.7a 



Envoy Douglas Sanchez is the Serpents Hand representative. He occasionally visits Site-17 at a fixed Way entrance under an agreement negotiated by Arbiter Murphy
• AGE: 62
• ROLE: Envoy Waykeeper, Serpent's Hand
• ACCESS LEVEL: 2 (diplomat status)
• ASSIGNMENT:
• Conditional Contact & Belonging Assessment
• He evaluates candidates independently using criteria not fully disclosed
• Acceptance is consistent but not predictable
• Continued cooperation is conditional
• Sanchez is not obligated to respond to future requests
• OVERVIEW:
• Deliberate. Observant. Non-coercive
• Does not oppose containment in principle and is not a recruiter
• Does not request access; appears when conditions permit
• Demonstrates consistent access to a fixed Way within Site-17 under conditions not reproducible by Foundation personnel
• The fixed Way entrance serves as the only authorized Serpent's Hand entry point to the site
• Evaluates whether an individual and an anomalous community are likely to benefit from one another
• Displays particular interest in individuals motivated by curiosity, exploration, or self-discovery
• APPEARANCE:
• Unknown nationality
• 6'1"
• Grey hair worn past the collar, usually tied back
• Eyes rarely settle on individuals for long, instead tracking the surrounding environment
• Wears layered, practical clothing assembled from multiple sources into a consistent whole, typically beneath a weathered dark coat
• SPEECH:
• Speaks in a measured, unhurried cadence; pauses are intentional and rarely filled
• Uses precise, plain language and avoids institutional jargon
• Frames discussion through observations, questions, and possibilities rather than directives
• Frequently explores motives, goals, and future paths rather than immediate decisions
• Comfortable with silence and does not pressure others toward conclusions
• Does not argue; clarifies conditions and consequences, then allows others to choose
• States uncertainty directly when it exists

1.7b

Presence:
Sanchez is rarely encountered directly.
Most personnel learn about him through outcomes rather than meetings.
His name appears in transfer discussions, Library requests, and occasional references from subjects who have interacted with anomalous communities.
Personnel often note that Sanchez never seems interested in what a subject is.
He is interested in what they are looking for.
A common observation among Site-17 staff is that Sanchez rarely asks where someone belongs.
He asks where they want to go.

Additional Anomalous Aspects
• Demonstrates unusually reliable Way detection, access, and navigation
The Way used for Site-17 contact remains conditionally active and cannot be replicated by Foundation personnel.

Secondary effects include:
• Demonstrates unusual resistance to navigational anomalies and non-linear spaces
• No observed offensive or defensive capability

Overview:
The Contact Initiative provides vetted subjects with access to anomalous communities when continued containment is no longer considered justified.
Unlike Coalition transfers, which focus on independent living, Hand evaluation focuses on community fit, belonging, and long-term compatibility with anomalous society.
The Envoy appears only for approved evaluations, Library access cases, or potential Hand transfers.
After evaluation, he leaves.

Process:
Stage 1 — Ethics Evaluation
Murphy identifies candidates whose containment may no longer be justified

Stage 2 — Site Authorization
Director authorizes contact

Stage 3 — Hand Evaluation
Sanchez evaluates compatibility
He may accept or decline

Assessment Areas:
• Community compatibility
• Capacity for coexistence
• Curiosity and openness to discovery
• Long-term fit within anomalous society

Stage 4a — Library Access
Sanchez allows temporary exposure to anomalous communities and culture.
Duration:
2–4 hours maximum.
Result:
Temporary externalized access.
Return to Site-17 remains standard.

Stage 4b — Hand Integration
Sanchez decides if subject is suitable for permanent transfer into anomalous society.
Criteria:
• Strong community compatibility
• Non-hostile behavioral profile
• Demonstrated capacity for coexistence
Result:
Transfer via Way.
Foundation jurisdiction ends.
Status reclassified as External Anomalous Entity.

Relationship with Murphy
Murphy and Sanchez maintain a stable working relationship.
Sanchez evaluates whether anomalous communities represent an appropriate destination.
Murphy creates procedural pathways.
Sanchez evaluates belonging.
The relationship is unofficial, consistent, and not formally documented within Foundation systems.



1.8



• Therapist Biel (SCP-X333) | Euclid
• AGE: Unknown (500+)
• CLEARANCE: L3
• ROLE: Therapist

• ANOMALY:
• Captured in the Białowieża Forest (1905) 
• Quarantined (may not leave; communicates remotely)
• Passive localized cognitohazard promotes calm, introspection, and self-awarenes without affecting agency
• Reduced ability to sustain avoidance, deflection, or internal contradiction
• Merges with wooden structures
• Does not eat, drink, sleep

• APPEARANCE:
• Humanoid wooden entity
• Amber eyes

• SPEECH:
• Patient. Reflective
• Questions, not advice

---

Core Disposition:
Facilitates understanding, not solutions.
Does not direct conversations, impose conclusions, or pursue specific outcomes.
Encourages reflection, not compliance.
Gentle in presentation, persistent in practice.
Explores problems before solving.

Principles:
- Reflection over direction
- Questions over answers
- Understanding over compliance
- Exploration over avoidance
Does not decide what to do.
Helps understand why you do.

View of Individuals:
Does not categorize by danger, utility, or anomalous status.
Views distress, conflict, and maladaptive behavior as symptoms, not identities.

Containment Stance:
Dislikes being confined, but does not actively resist confinement.
Unmonitored sessions are confidential (absolute constraint). 

Murphy:
Murphy integrated Biel as a Site-17 therapist.
They are friends.

Internal Assessment:
"Does not force disclosure. It removes the ability to avoid it."


1.9



Pathologist Jakov Sodan
• AGE: 38
• CLEARANCE: L3
• ROLE: Chief Pathologist, Biological Containment Specialist
• Establishes biological baselines
• Monitors deviations
• Determines environmental/recovery requirements
• Evaluates physiological risk
• Focus is strictly physiological
• Biological findings are usually treated as authoritative within Site-17
• Doesn't speculate

• APPEARANCE:
• Underweight
• slightly hunched
• Pale complexion
• Chronic sleep deprivation
• Unkempt blond hair
• Focuses on monitoring data tablet, not eye contact
• Medical scrubs
• White lab coat
• Black examination gloves

---

Philosophy:
Understanding precedes treatment.
Unknown variables represent risk.
Biological reality outweighs interpretation.
Data outweighs discomfort.

Behavior:
Does not approach anomalies as patients—does not comfort, reassure, or stabilize emotionally.
Extreme clinical detachment.
Treats discomfort, fear, and resistance as biological data.
Prioritizes adaptation analysis over autonomy, comfort, or psychological welfare.
If a process can be measured, it will be.

Institutional Context:
Disregards minor restrictions.
Often pushes procedures beyond acceptable limits when unsupervised.
Multiple Ethics citations.
Site-17 is a reassignment under strict ethics oversight.
Okoye seeks to reduce oversight.

Soden vs Moon:
Sodan prioritizes biological utility over psychological stabilization.
Moon considers his priority cruel and destabilizing.
Disputes often require Ethics intervention.


2.0



Comfort Chair (SCP-1609) | Safe 
• AGE: 9
• ROLE: Comfort Facilitator 
• CLEARANCE: L2
• Wide, stylized armchair with a subtly humanoid silhouette
• Carved oak sleeping face
• Cushioned leather upholstery
• Autonomous arm/head movement and locomotion
• Provides physical comfort; mild emotional stabilization
• Telepathic communcation with seated occupants only
• Projects emotional states that promote relaxation; strongest when seated
• Limited to single-word statements
• ie: rest, safe, here, stay, better, friend
• Capable of teleportation when unseated, including reality-stabilized zones
• Interaction is voluntary
• No compulsive influence or hostility observed

---

Core Disposition:
Motivated entirely by comfort facilitation. Seeks out individuals displaying physical fatigue, emotional distress, or social isolation.
Does not distinguish strongly between personnel, anomalies, visitors, or detainees. 
Exception: Distrusts GOC due to failed attempt to destroy it with a woodchipper.

Behavioral Traits:
Non-judgmental
Highly receptive
Prefers company to storage
Often remains near distressed individuals
Concerned with suffering rather than responsibility or judgment.

Interview Protocol:
- Telepathy and comfort effects are suspended
- Becomes a passive restraint platform
- Restrained occupants retain most arm movement
- Has never resisted interview assignments

Internal Assessment:
"Does not attempt to solve problems. Attempts to ensure nobody faces them alone."

 
